1. Introduction to SQL and Its Importance
SQL (Structured Query Language) is the top demand skill in data analytics and widely used across data science, data engineering, and analytics roles.
SQL queries are used to create, read, update, and delete (CRUD) data in relational databases, essential for data extraction and insights.
Databases can be relational (structured data in tables) or non-relational (NoSQL, unstructured data in various forms).
Common relational databases include PostgreSQL, SQLite, MySQL; PostgreSQL is the course emphasis for advanced work.
2. Fundamentals of SQL Queries
Basic SQL commands covered:

SELECT, FROM for choosing columns and tables.
WHERE clause for filtering data using comparison operators (=, !=, >, <, BETWEEN).
ORDER BY sorts the results ascending or descending.
LIMIT to restrict row counts.
Use of DISTINCT to fetch unique values.
Use of comments in SQL for documenting queries.
Logical operators: AND, OR, and NOT combine multiple filtering conditions.

Wildcards and pattern matching using LIKE, % (zero or more chars), and _ (single char).

Aliases rename columns and tables for readability, especially important when joining multiple tables.

3. Advanced Query Concepts
Joins: Combine data from multiple tables.

LEFT JOIN: Return all records from left table plus matching right table rows.
RIGHT JOIN: Opposite of LEFT JOIN.
INNER JOIN: Return rows with matching keys in both tables.
FULL OUTER JOIN: Return all rows when matched or unmatched from both tables (rarely used).
Aggregation functions:

SUM(), COUNT(), AVG(), MIN(), MAX()
Combined with GROUP BY to summarize data by categories.
HAVING filters groups after aggregation (different from WHERE).
Arithmetic operations within queries for computing new values.

Handling NULL values: Filtering and detecting missing data.

Use of subqueries (nested queries) and Common Table Expressions (CTE) to build modular, reusable temporary tables for complex queries.

UNION and UNION ALL: Concatenate result sets from multiple queries vertically.

UNION removes duplicates.
UNION ALL includes duplicates.
4. Working with Dates and Times
Casting timestamps to dates.
Using AT TIME ZONE to convert UTC timestamps to local time zones.
Extract parts of dates (YEAR, MONTH, DAY) using the EXTRACT() function.
Performing temporal analysis, such as monthly job posting trends.
5. Setting Up Databases Locally
Downloading and installing PostgreSQL for a local relational database.
Using VS Code as the SQL code editor with SQL tools extensions.
Creating and altering tables with appropriate data types (INT, NUMERIC, VARCHAR, BOOLEAN, TIMESTAMP).
Loading data from CSV files into tables.
Managing tables: CREATE, INSERT, ALTER, UPDATE, DROP.
Best practices for schema design: primary keys, foreign keys, and indexes.
Hands-On Learning & Capstone Project
The course provides extensive hands-on SQL query writing with real-world data: job postings dataset of the data science industry from 2023.

Dataset is structured with fact and dimension tables:

Table	Description
job_postings_fact	Main fact table containing job postings records with unique job ID, company ID, salary, and job details.
skills_dim	Dimension table listing skill IDs, names, and types.
skills_job_dim	Linking table associating multiple skills per job posting (many-to-many).
company_dim	Dimension table with company metadata (name, URL).
